## Decisions and rationale

### Cached counts on students (vs computed on read)

Read-time COUNT() across thousands of attendance rows is slow on a roster page. Cache total, gi_classes, etc. on the students row, kept in sync via trigger. O(1) reads. Mitigation against drift: attendance trigger, promotion trigger, manual recompute RPC, numeric columns (migration 47).

### Legacy IDs alongside UUIDs

Every table has a UUID PK; many also have a legacy_id text column (e.g., fwb) for URLs and stable references. Survives env changes, reads better in URLs/Slack.

### Whitelist as separate table

Authentication against auth.users; authorization against public.whitelist. Separates identity from access.

### parent_user_id on students (not a join table)

Each kid has one or two parents; modeled as scalar FK + denorm secondary fields. Simpler queries and RLS. Post-transition: parent_user_id remains as guardian read-only.

### Status on attendance (going / present / absent)

3-state status: going = intent (unconfirmed), present = instructor-confirmed (counts via class_value), absent = confirmed no-show.

### Numeric type for class counts (migration 47)

SUM(class_value) where class_value is numeric. Preserves fractional precision (three 0.25 classes = 0.75, not rounded to 1).

### Head Instructor Notes: dedicated table, not staff.feedback JSONB (migration 56)

Originally notes lived in staff.feedback JSONB. Problem: the staff_select policy is public (everyone can see who teaches), so the JSONB notes were readable by any authenticated user. Head Instructor Notes are sensitive admin-to-staff communication. Fix: a dedicated staff_notes table with owner-only SELECT RLS, written only via SECURITY DEFINER RPCs. staff.feedback is now legacy (emptied to '[]').

This supersedes the earlier "staff.feedback as JSONB" decision. The feedback table (instructor → student) is unaffected — different audience, different storage.

### kids_unit_summary as a SECURITY DEFINER aggregate (migration 57)

Child safety: parents must not SELECT other kids' rows (names, photos, attendance). RLS enforces that. But parents still benefit from non-identifying context about the kids program (how many kids, belt spread). A SECURITY DEFINER function returns counts only — total and by-belt tallies — never rows, names, or photos. This is the data source for the count-only kids view (vs the named peer roster adults get).

### wall_reactions polymorphic (Oss)

target_type / target_id rather than a promotion-specific FK, so future feed item types (competition posts, G21) reuse the same table and the Oss control works on them with zero rework. Writes go through the toggle_oss RPC for atomicity (no read-modify-write race) and to enforce adults-only visibility in one place.

### set_event_participation RPC (vs direct array writes)

events write is admin-only (RLS), and competing/supporting are arrays on the events row. A client toggling its own participation would either be blocked by RLS or race two concurrent read-modify-writes. The RPC runs SECURITY DEFINER, resolves the caller to their own legacy_id, and mutates the arrays atomically server-side — self-service participation without opening event writes to everyone.

### users name split (migration 54)

Parent self-edit uses two inputs (First + Last) to match the students/staff edit pattern. full_name stays canonical and is kept in sync (first + ' ' + last) on self-edit, plus the staff/student name-sync triggers propagate to users.full_name, so existing consumers of users.full_name keep working.

### Per-policy structure (one policy per CMD)

Separate policies per SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE rather than a single ALL policy, so the security model is auditable per operation. (promotions is a deliberate exception with two SELECT policies — base + adult-peer — OR-combined to layer Wall visibility on top of the private base policy.)

### Social handles as JSONB (migration 49)

JSONB on staff and students instead of a column per platform. Social platforms come and go; most users fill 1-2 handles; querying by platform is uncommon. Arbitrary keys without schema changes.

### has_mybjj_gi naming

Boolean, Postgres convention (positive prefix has_, lowercase). Real schema is has_mybjj_gi (migration 49).

### bjj_start_date separate from joined_at (migration 66)

Two distinct dates:
- **joined_at** = students.created_at, when the row was inserted (i.e., joined the myBJJ app)
- **bjj_start_date** = when the student first started practicing BJJ anywhere (any academy, any country)

A student who has trained for years before the academy adopted myBJJ shouldn't appear as "Training since May 2026" — that's the join date, not the journey origin. bjj_start_date is optional, month-precision, validated ≤ today and ≤ joined_at. The journey timeline renders "Started BJJ — {Mon YYYY}" as the first entry when populated, and a muted "Date not set" placeholder otherwise (with an inline "Add date" link for staff viewers).

### edit_student_self clear-support pattern (migration 67)

Most fields in edit_student_self use `COALESCE(p_payload->>'col', col)` so absence of the key in the payload preserves the existing value. This is what we want for fields you don't intend to clear (e.g. full_name). For fields where clear is a legitimate user action (bjj_start_date, weight_kg, height_cm, has_mybjj_gi, social_handles), the function uses `CASE WHEN p_payload ? 'col' THEN NULLIF(...,'')::col_type ELSE col END` — the JSON-key check lets the caller distinguish "key omitted → preserve" from "key present with empty string → clear to NULL".
